segments.text: In 1997, we were in Bandon, Oregon.
And would you please tell me your full name, rank, and serial number?
Okay, my name is Lloyd G. Lyman, Jr.
I was born May 16, 1923.
Where?
In Medford, Oregon.
And your family, father, what were they doing?
My father was a bull of the woods.
He was a logging superintendent for the California Fruit Growers Exchange, which is the Sunkist Orange.
They made boxes for Sunkist Orange.
Is that right?
That was the excuse they had for getting into the lumber business.
And did you have brothers and sisters?
I had one sister who was three years younger than I had.
She lives in Ashland today.
And did you spend your young life in Medford?
I grew up in Medford, yes.
I never left home until I was left to go to college.
And where did you go to college?
I went to Reed College in Portland.
R-E-E-I-D. No, double E. R-E-E-D, okay.
How did you get to Reed College?
On a scholarship.
Is that a presidential?
Non-denominational, yeah.
It's like...
It's a good school.
It's similar to Swarthmore, or to the little Ivy League schools, or something like that.
It's a good school.
What is it, about 1,200, 1,400, 1,500, or more?
I think it's about 1,200 now, but when I went there, it was less than...
Oh, is that right?
Yeah, the entering classes were limited to 100, and they never graduated more than about 70.
So, but that all changed with World War II, because for one thing, people like myself, it took me eight years to get through school.
When did you start?
Okay, you entered the class in 1940, and then what happened?
Then, three years into that, I went into the Navy, and I was in the Navy for a couple of years.
You enlisted, drafted, all of your bombs.
I was a 90-day wonder.
Oh, is that right?
Yeah.
I started out as a naval aviation cadet, got washed out, and got a commission as a deck officer.
Did you go to sea?
I went to, I spent about a year and a half in the Pacific, at the end of the war in the South Pacific, on a landing craft.
I was a landing boat officer on the A.K.A.
Okay.
I tell you,
Of course, I came along a bit later, but you know, he said, for assignment I wanted sea duty in the Pacific.
I got shore duty in the Atlantic.
I really did.
I really wanted to destroy it.
Oh, what a great life that would have been.
Well, I tried to, I think I saved my life by getting washed out of the
Naval Aviation, I couldn't land to a spot.
If I was in the Air Force, I could have been okay, because they come in and they don't stall out over us.
I was stationed in Jacksonville Naval Air Station.
Those guys are insane.
They drink all night and cry all day.
So you're in service, you go to, you're in Tokyo, in Japan.
We were in the first, at the end of the war, we were
in Subic Bay, practicing to land in Japan, to attack Japan when the war ended.
So we were all loaded up.
And we were the first task force into Japan when the war ended.
And we were in Japan the day that MacArthur was on the Missouri.
We went to sail right past the stern of the Iowa that he was on.
I forget the name of the battleship.
Missouri.
It was the Missouri, yes.
Yeah, it was the Missouri.
And I remember seeing that peglated little
Japanese guy that surrendered.
It was one of the officers that surrendered.
He only had one leg.
And we went right, our ship went right up past the stern during all these ceremonies.
That's memorable.
Yeah, that was memorable.
And then how long did you stay in Japan?
Well, after that we took Japanese troops that were in Manchuria back to Japan.
evacuated them.
On American ships?
Yes, on the A.K.A.s.
A.K.A.
is the Cargo Attack.
And then we took Chinese nationalist troops out of Hong Kong to North China to feed them to the communists.
We unloaded.
We made about five or six trips to places like Tsingtao
Tsing-Wang-Tao, and a whole bunch of northern ports.
You don't think about that?
That would have been part of the end of the war?
Well, no, they were fighting.
This was when the communists were coming out of it.
Oh, okay.
That war had already started.
Yes, they were headed for trouble.
Anyhow, that's when we came home.
And so you got out of service in Muscovado, where you probably went.
Well, it must have been 1946, and then I went back to Reed, and another year and a half was all done.
to graduate school.
What'd you finish in?
American history.
I went to graduate school at Berkeley.
I was in history there.
And after I got a master's degree, and in the process of doing that, I knew I didn't want to become a teacher.
This guy that I
got my master's with was, he kept asking me what I was going to do, because I told him I didn't want to be a teacher, and he told me that the library school was looking for men.
So I went to the library school, and I got a library degree in 1950.
And then I went to work at Caltech, and I was the assistant librarian there for a couple of years.
I was there for five years.
And the library school started a doctoral program, and I was invited to come back to participate in that.
And they gave me a, I was a teaching fellow or something at that sort of library school.
really bored, I decided I didn't want to do it.
For one thing, I didn't believe in a doctorate for librarians.
That was a waste of time.
So, one of the instructors in the library school was the ex-wife of the director of the University of California Press.
And she told me that they were looking for people
And I went down and talked to the director, and he hired me, and I was the assistant to the director.
And the director was?
August Peruget.
F-R-U-G-E with an accent over the E. And tell me something about the University of California Press.
Okay.
It was founded, I believe, in 1893, and
And it would have been one of the earliest?
It was among the earliest, yes, along with Chicago, Johns Hopkins, and Columbia.
So it could have been one of the first public universities.
It may have been the first public.
I think that's right.
That's interesting.
Yeah.
Chicago is the oldest.
Oldest, yeah.
It's a couple of years older.
Well, Chicago was founded in 1893.
Well, maybe I've got Cal five years too soon, but I know that Cal was started before the turn of the century, and I know Chicago is the oldest university press in the United States.
and Thorstein Bedman, and Bedman went to teach at Chicago in 93 when it opened, I believe is correct.
I think that's correct.
I'll have to check that.
Anyway, okay.
So, and what kind of format or what was the California Press doing?
Anything in terms of characterizing it?
Well, this was, I went there in 1956.
And this was a big time for university presses.
There was this legislation that federal money was going into libraries to support book purchases.
And university presses were expanding at a ferocious rate.
This was a great decade.
The 50s into the 60s was a great time for university presses.
Among other things, I think that the University of Texas was founded in this period.
And many other universities began their publishing programs in this period.
For South Carolina and Texas also.
Yes.
I think South Carolina was already established by then.
LSU was older.
LSU was 20s or 30s.
Do you know?
It's possible.
We'll come back to that in a minute.
But anyway.
I think we can look for some of that stuff.
So this was good.
That's a way to mention that.
This was a good time for the university press expansion and so forth.
And there were a great number of people my age who were recruited at this time.
Most of us had no previous publishing experience.
We learned on the job.
And that's what I got.
I started out as assistant to the director and I became an assistant director.
And I had, I got to do everything.
For a while I was a copy editor.
I did everything but the actual direct sale and selling.
I never hit the bookstore.
But I ended up being responsible for, as assistant director, I was responsible for all the activities except
the editing.
But I was also an editor.
They had what they called sponsoring editors in California.
And these people were responsible for certain areas, subject areas.
And I had the local history mostly.
I had the stuff, most of the stuff I had was what no one else wanted.
California had a big list.
California became one of the top two or three in terms of quantity.
Chicago has always been the first.
And Harvard, Cal were next.
Columbia, Princeton, Yale.
Hopkins wasn't very big, but it became big, and it is now.
It's a lot bigger now.
And how long were you in California?
16 years.
Is that right?
Yes.
So you left...
In the 70s, in the 72 or something like that.
Why?
Well... And you went to LSU?
More or less, yeah.
Okay, well, okay, hold on, okay.
For personal reasons, let's leave that.
I'll tell you after Trinity.
All right.
And then...
four, three or four, I went to LSU.
And I was the executive editor and the sales and promotion manager.
Under?
Under Les Filabal.
Charles East had already resigned, and Dick Wentworth had already gone to Illinois.
Philomon is P-H-I-L-L-I-V-A-U-N?
That's close.
We can check this.
I have an AAUP directory.
Yeah, I can really get addicted to all of them.
I like these.
Turn it off a minute, and I'll get to that directly.
So you go to LSU about 73, and you're a...
I was assistant editor, associate director.
I was executive editor.
Executive editor.
And sales and promotion manager.
Sales and promotion.
I got it.
And what's going on at LSU?
Well, at this time, LSU was growing, was going fast.
And they had the...
The old style series.
Yeah, but what's that book called?
Something of fools.
Ship of fools.
No, not the ship, the other one.
Yeah.
OK, let's turn it back on.
OK, so LSU's leading book right at the moment was The Confederacy of Dunces.
And were you there when that book was published?
Yes.
Well, we were negotiating when I was there.
But I think it got published later, in 1980 or something like that.
Or it got the prize in 1980.
So those were good years for LSU.
LSU had good years, 50s, 60s, 70s, and maybe still is.
And the Old South series was really classy.
Yes.
I think under Philip Baum's direction, the press has flourished, and it's continued as far as I know.
You're at LSU now, 73 until when?
I was there about a year and a half.
And I believe it was 1974 that Frank Gordloff approached me about coming to A&M to be his successor.
Can you tell me a little bit about that approach?
He and I attended one of the national meetings
And I believe this was one that was at Yale.
I think that's what it was.
And during that meeting, he backed me into a corner and told me that he would like me to apply for the job of associate director at A&M with the idea of becoming his successor.
He was planning to retire in a couple of years.
OK. Why you?

He was a very good friend of August Truget's, and I, although I never can prove this, I suspect that he had some conversation at some point with August Truget about finding a successor, and August must have recommended me.
He came highly recommended.
I got some very good
recommendations from both August Pruget and the other assistant director at Cal, Bill Lilley, who was a demon editor.
He was terrific as a painter.
But those two both gave me... And let's see, so what do you think about this approach?
Are you receptive?
You can't really say no.
Well, you can't say no to Frank Wardlaw under any circumstances.
And shortly after that, I... And Phil Vaughan was...
In fact, I still have... Because Frank had written him first.
Yes, yes, I think that's right.
I didn't know that.
Yeah, I did.
I did.
You've got the documents, yeah.
Anyway, then we...
Leigh and I went to College Station, which neither of us had the faintest, really, idea of where College Station was.
The only thing I knew about College Station was that that's where John Kimbrough came from for the national championship football team sometime before.
But I had no idea where it was, where College Station was.
I had a vague idea of where Austin was, but I'd never been to Texas, ever.
And I'm sure it would have seemed more unusual if we hadn't spent close to two years in Louisiana.
Yeah.
Because that was our first experience with any southwest, southern, whatever.
Yeah, that's a different world.
Both of them are different.
Oh, yes.
I'd probably stay in a really different place than South Louisiana.
Oh, yeah.
Because we know we went there from Lafayette.
Yeah.
Still getting adjusted.
No.
Of course, Lafayette's a totally different place.
Oh, yes.
Okay, so you came to College Station, and what happened when you got there?
This is your exploratory.
Had you already accepted?
We'd accepted.
We came over and were interviewed again by Frank and Jack Williams.
We were formally offered the job, and we accepted.
What was Williams' role in that positive reviews?
I believe...
He was watching and listening and supporting?
Yes, I believe that it would have been impossible to have gotten the job unless he concurred.
I think that he was very interested in the press.

Yeah, that's what, you know, Joe Morris, I was reading one of them, and that was one of the most impressive things with him, is when he wasn't praying so much, but Williams' great interest, that really reassured me.
Well, I doubt that it could have happened, that Frank could have even gone there without William's interest and strong support.

And he did, I don't know whether we should also mention the fact that several times during the time that I was there, at the end of William's career there, he diverted some donations that came to his office, small amounts of money, like $10,000, $15,000,
and handed them to the press.
Let's reiterate that and make it clear.
So any immediate impression of any of the press situation at that time?
That's a good question.
Sometimes you get interesting answers.
I've got something I'll show you.
I wrote back to one of the people, one of the assistants.
administrative assistant at LSU, my impression of Texas.
But it was, it was a total, it was completely outside my experience, and it certainly was outside Leah's experience.
She had never been exposed to this kind of like world at all.
One of the things that impressed me
And I remember the very first was the extreme, I guess you'd call it, formality.
All the, all the, you could identify all the faculty members, I thought, because they all wore black suits and white ties.
Did you remember that?
Well, I certainly, that was, you could, just every one of them, it seemed like.
And it began to change.
during the decade that I was there, pretty soon it wasn't, you couldn't do that anymore.
But it seemed like... That's interesting, yeah.
It was almost like a uniform, for heaven's sake.
Yeah.
No, I don't mean that.
I guess I keep thinking of Lloyd Taylor in history, who was so different, you know, I guess.
But anyway, history was a different problem the rest of it.
That's interesting.
And the other thing that the...
The thing that neither of us was aware of was... Of course, you had been in California.
Yes, yes.
And A&M was in the backwater of all the social, cultural change.
Yes.
That's true.
That's correct.
Okay, I got you.
Yeah.
The other thing that I couldn't, that was odd, was that every...
faculty member with, there was a very insistence on doctor.
And at California, it was all Mr. or Miss or Mrs.
There was never, no matter how many degrees a person had, they never used them, used the designation job.
Yeah, Missouri was kind of getting in that vogue and all those things.
Yeah, yeah.
That's interesting.
Okay.
So you and Leah will move to College Station.
Yes.
Or Brian, whichever.
Yes.
When?
In September.
It had to be in September, probably.
Yeah, I believe it was September.
And it must have been 70.
You probably started September the 1st, 1977?
No.
Oh, no, no.
75 or something like that.
I'll check up there.
I know that.
That's got to be on the record.
I don't know.
Yeah, it is.
I keep
Seventy, it must have been seventy-five.
Yeah, it had to be.
I think it was seventy-five.
Yeah, because the pressed artists that came the first, seventy-four.
That's, see that, yeah.
I mean, and Frank Fedow wrote that nice piece.
Thank goodness he wrote that in the beginning.
That's with chapter one.
Uh-huh.
Yeah, yeah, I think that sounds more like it, Henry.
I think it was seventy-five.
Okay, and now when you came, were there any instructions or...
directions or format that the Whitehall laid out, that here's what we're going to do?
No, there wasn't anything like that.
It was either he assumed that I was aware of what they wanted to do, or he just assumed or took all that under his own hat.
The thing he did
that I really helped a great deal.
He took me around and introduced me to dozens of people all over the state.
Businessmen, politicians, other faculty people,
authors, and he also got me into the Texas Institute of Letters, which I had no reason.
I mean, I think at the time that I was there, there were only a couple of other people in the Institute of Letters.
One of them was Vandiver.
Vandiver hated it.
He had nothing to do with it.
And the other was your colleague.
Milton.
And as far as I know, those are the only other ones.
And Frank.
Frank was .
Was there anything unique or distinctive or peculiar you thought about?
Wardlaw's relationship to the rest of the world in Texas.
I'm not sure what question I'm asking.
I think he would have been a perfectly successful politician.
I think he had a wider acquaintance than most politicians.
He told me once that one of the people that impressed him most in his whole life was LBJ.
LBJ kind of overwhelmed him, frankly.
came out second man in that confrontation.
That's good.
But he was very impressed by LBJ, and he had numerous encounters with him, apparently.
Yeah, because that world seems so unique and pure and distinct, and you know, there's just a little charisma or something going there that's strange, and you don't see that.
Frank had a knack for
or people for important people.
Important.
And he just had a way.
Instinct.
Yeah, somehow he could get to it, and I don't know how the heck he did it.
Oh, obviously.
Do you think, what was his role as a director when you came, and also, I want to define your role as an associate?
Well, there wasn't any question.
He was in charge, and he was
really the catalyst of establishing the reputation of getting the, he was looking for the authors, and directing, he raised a lot of
And do you think that was, what was uppermost on his mind in terms of, was it funding, was he building the funding?
I think funding was, yeah, because he had no, an unlimited amount of capital to work with, and he had no assurance of more so far as... No, no, he didn't.
The point about this revolving funding, was that unique in the publishing business?
you know, setting up those series with all these funds.
Oh, yes, this was all in the wind.
This happened over and over again in that period in the late 50s into the 60s into the 70s.
And he had had tremendous experience doing this at Texas especially, not so much South Carolina.
That was too early.
But this is all, it was part of the whole of
university presses everywhere.
That was a characteristic of the university press business at that time.
That was not something unique or distinctive to Frank Washington.
No, no, no.
Harvard, there's the Bancroft series in Harvard, and all sorts of odd things happened with the way the money came.
Sometimes it was sought, and sometimes people just brought it in and

That Bancroft thing at Harvard, somebody, I think it's Bancroft, anyway, some couple whose son was killed in World War II just walked in the door of Wilson's office and said, we'd like to make a memorial to our son who loved books.
For that time, it was enormous.
Now, Frank's solicitations were almost invariably $75,000 to the nation.
Why?
I don't know.
I wish he had been a little more aggressive, because I think, considering the influence he had with some of these people, he could have gotten a lot more.
But that was the number.
Any time you saw it?
Yes.

75 you need 75 and then 75 over there he he usually would would look at it i think his perspective was to say you need enough to us to do the first book or the first two books a couple of books and then depend on income from sales and some of these uh series it was unrealistic it would have been better if he'd had
bigger amount that would have allowed a longer term development, a series of developments.
Yeah, because you can send things bombs, you know, they do that.
But he was an absolute ace at going out and getting, like you say, 75, 50,000 bucks.
Now, and what is your primary function when you first arrived?
Everything?
I was in a learning mode, mostly, and I
The difference between my experience at Cal, the biggest difference, and at Texas A&M, was that at Cal, it was a big organization by when it was depressed then.
There were a hundred employees.
I don't think there are that many now, but there were.
It was very diffused.
People had little compartmentalized

responsibilities and the director there was more of a juggler more of a he was running he was handling all the sub departments whereas frank ran everything frank was his own production manager frank was his own acquisitions frank was his own salesman
